Consider this code

```
    try:
        carrier = {}
        span.tracer.inject(span, SOME_CUSTOM_FORMAT, carrier)
        do_something(carrier)
    except opentracing.UnsupportedFormatException:
        pass  # it's possible tracer does not support out custom format
    except:
        log.exception('Failed to inject tracing span into headers')
        metric.intCounter()
```

Without a mandate for the tracers (including the Noop tracer) to return an exception on unknown format there is no way in the code to know if the situation is legitimate (i.e. tracer does not support given custom format) or a genuine error (bad context propagation or what not).

## Issue description

When a type has `operator==` defined, but it returns something other than `bool` or something that can be converted to `bool`, the detection logic in `container_traits<T>::test_comparable` fails and returns `true` when it should return `false`. Then code gets instantiated in `vector_if_equal_operator` which then fails to compile.

It should additionally to the existence of `operator==` be checked whether the return value can be converted to `bool`. But my metaprogramming skills are not good enough to come up with a clean solution...

## Reproducible example code
```cpp
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <pybind11/stl_bind.h>

template<typename T>
struct vec { T a; T b; };

template<typename T>
vec<bool> operator==(const vec<T>& l, const vec<T>& r) {
    return {l.a == r.a, l.b == r.b};
}

PYBIND11_MODULE(test, m) {
    pybind11::bind_vector<std::vector<vec<float>>>(m, "float_vec_vector");
}
```

The actual type for which I ran into this is `cv::Mat` from OpenCV. And I worked around it for now with:
```cpp
namespace pybind11::detail {
    template<> struct is_comparable<cv::Mat> : std::false_type {};
}
```

Though I know it might be considered a case of "stupid code, don't write that", I just found the following way of segfaulting a pybind11 extension module:

```C++
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>
#include <iostream>

struct Test {
	int x = 42;
};

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_PLUGIN(test) {
	py::module m("test");
	
	py::class_<Test /* implicitly held by std::unique_ptr */>(m, "Test")
		.def(py::init<>())
	;
	
	m.def("f", [] (std::shared_ptr<Test> test) {
		std::cout << "Here" << std::endl;
		std::cout << test->x << std::endl;
		std::cout << "There" << std::endl;
	});
	
	return m.ptr();
}
```

Calling function `f` with an argument of type `Test` does not result in a type exception, but segfaults Python:

```Python
>>> import test
>>> test.f(test.Test())
Here
42
There
Segmentation fault (core dumped)
```
(Note that you might need to repeat this, as it seems that sometimes the 'undefined behaviour' causes nothing to happen. I am guess this is the case because the layouts of `std::unique_ptr` and `std::shared_ptr` overlap and so the pointer itself is not invalid.)

As far as I see, the problem lies in the fact that 'copyable_holder_caster' does not check (and has no way of checking?) the type of the holder once the held type matches (i.e., [this line in cast.h](https://github.com/pybind/pybind11/blob/0f5ec0a87e3d3879cd70740422adf3e3728a9d84/include/pybind11/cast.h#L959). This is actually how I found this way of segfaulting, by trying to understand the casting mechanism, rather than writing such stupid code.

I am aware you have to make a rather severe programming mistake to trigger this, but it does not seem not to match the philosophy of pybind11 regarding type safety, and since it could not find a previous bug report on this, I reckoned this might be interesting.

Allow queries like:
```
{
    Species {
        in_Animal_OfSpecies @fold {
            out_Entity_Related {
                name @output(out_name: "related_list")
            }
        }
    }
}
```

We currently don't support traversals from inside a `@fold` scope.

I want to call some python functions using numpy and sklearn from Java.
The first call always works, but when instantiating a second Jep the JVM crashes with an  EXCEPTION_ACCESS_VIOLATION when calling the import in the eval statement.
The example works with other libs such as math etc.

A minimal example:


	import jep.Jep;
	import jep.JepException;

	public class JavaTest {
		private static void execPy() {
			try (Jep jep = new Jep(false)) {
				jep.eval("import numpy as np");
				jep.eval("x = np.add(1.0, 4.0)");
				double result = (double) jep.getValue("x");
				System.out.println(result);
			} catch (JepException e) {
				e.printStackTrace();
			}
		}

		public static void main(String[] args) {
			for (int i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
				execPy();
			}
		}

	}


